{"parse":{"title":"tongue","pageid":5783,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Tongue}}\n==English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|tong|tonge|toong|toongue|toung|tounge|toungue|tung|tunge||obsolete}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|tongue}}, a late spelling of {{m|enm|tonge|tong(e)|id=tongue}}, {{m|enm|tunge|tung(e)}}, from {{inh|en|ang|tunge}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*tungā||tongue}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*tungǭ||tongue}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*dn̥ǵʰwéh₂s||tongue}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|tong||tongue}}, {{cog|de|Zunge||tongue}}, {{cog|da,nb,nn|tunge||tongue}}, {{cog|fo,is,sv|tunga||tongue}}, {{cog|got|𐍄𐌿𐌲𐌲𐍉||tongue}}, {{cog|ga|teanga||tongue}}, {{cog|ast|-}} and {{cog|ca|llengua||tongue}}, {{cog|an|luenga||tongue}}, {{cog|fr|langue||tongue}}, {{cog|gl,la|lingua||tongue}}, {{cog|roa-leo|llingua||tongue}}, {{cog|mwl|lhéngua||tongue}}, {{cog|pt|língua||tongue}}, {{cog|es|lengua||tongue}}, {{cog|be|-}} and {{cog|ru|язык||tongue}}, {{cog|bg|ези́к||tongue}}, {{cog|cs|-}} and {{cog|sk|jazyk||tongue}}, {{cog|mk|јазик||tongue}}, {{cog|pl|język||tongue}}, {{cog|sh|jèzik||tongue}}, {{cog|sl|jézik||tongue}}, {{cog|uk|язи́к||tongue}}, {{cog|fa|زبان|tr=zabân||tongue}}, {{cog|sa|जि॒ह्वा||tongue}}. {{doublet|en|language|lingua}}.\n\nThe expected modern spelling, both phonetically and etymologically, would be {{m|en|tung}}. Using ⟨on⟩ for ⟨un⟩ was fairly common in {{m+|enm|-}}; compare e.g. {{m|enm|yong||young}}. The final ⟨gue⟩ arose to prevent {{m|enm||tonge}} being misread with a [[soft g|soft]] {{IPAchar|/dʒ/}}. However, this spelling only became common at a time when the final ⟨e⟩ was already largely silent, so it is not clear why it was not simply dropped instead.<ref>Oxford University Press. (n.d.). Tongue, n., Etymology. In Oxford English dictionary. Retrieved June 27, 2025, from https://doi.org/10.1093/OED/2664387729</ref> Perhaps the spelling was influenced directly by {{cog|fr|langue||tongue}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/tʌŋ/|a=RP,US,Canada}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-tongue.ogg|a=US}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-tongue.ogg|a=UK}}\n* {{IPA|en|/tʊŋɡ/|/tɒŋɡ/|a=Northern England}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ʌŋ|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|en|tong|qq=northern form with /ɒ/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|~}}\n[[File:Papillite linguale familiale.png|thumb|right|A tongue ''(sense 1)'']]\n\n# {{senseid|en|anatomy}} The flexible muscular [[organ]] in the [[mouth]] that is used to [[move]] [[food]] around, for [[tasting]] and that is moved into various positions to modify the [[flow]] of [[air]] from the [[lung]]s in order to produce different sounds in [[speech]].\n#: {{syn|en|glossa|lingua}}\n#* {{c.|1515–1516}}, published 1568, {{w|John Skelton}}, ''Againſt venemous tongues enpoyſoned with ſclaunder and falſe detractions &c.'':\n#*: But lering and lurking here and there like ſpies,<br>The devil tere their '''tunges''' and pike out their ies!\n# {{lb|en|countable|uncountable}} Such an [[organ]], as taken from [[animal]]s and used for food (especially from [[cow]]s).\n#: {{ux|en|cold '''tongue''' with mustard}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1902|author=w:E. Nesbit|title=w:Five Children and It|location=New York|publisher=Dodd, Mead|year_published=1905|chapter=4|page=136|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/17314/17314-h/17314-h.htm\n|passage=However you eat them, '''tongue''' and chicken and new bread are very good things, and no one minds being sprinkled a little with soda-water on a really fine hot day.}}\n# Any similar organ, such as the [[lingual]] [[ribbon]], or [[odontophore]], of a [[mollusk]]; the [[proboscis]] of a [[moth]] or [[butterfly]]; or the [[lingua]] of an [[insect]].\n# {{sid|en|language}} {{lb|en|metonym}} A [[language]].\n#: {{syn|en|idiom|language|lingo|q3=colloquial}}\n#: {{ux|en|He was speaking in his native '''tongue'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Spenser Complaints|The Ruines of Time|url=http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A12774.0001.001|text={{...}} {{w|Tower of Babel|that great Towre}}, which is so much renownd<br>For '''tongues''' confusion in [[Holy Writ|holie writ]],}}\n#* {{RQ:Swift Gulliver's Travels|part=2|page=178|text=When I pointed to any thing, she told me the Name of it in her own '''Tongue''', so that in a few Days I was able to call for whatever I had a mind to.}}\n#* {{RQ:Hardy Return of the Native|I|7|text=To dwell on a [[heath]] without studying its meanings was like wedding a foreigner without learning his '''tongue'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Maugham Of Human Bondage|chapter=LXXXVI|passage=“You should read Spanish,” he said. “It is a noble '''tongue'''. {{...|It has not the mellifluousness of Italian, Italian is the language of tenors and organ-grinders, but it has grandeur: it does not ripple like a brook in a garden, but it surges tumultuous like a mighty river in flood.}}”}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|year=1956|writer=w:Cyril Hume|title=w:Forbidden Planet|role=w:Robby the Robot|passage=If you do not speak English I am at your disposal with 187 other languages along with their various dialects and sub-'''tongues'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Achebe Things Fall Apart|chapter=23|page=200|passage=Many of them come from distant places and although they speak your '''tongue''' they are ignorant of your customs.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2002|author=w:Jeffrey Eugenides|title={{w|Middlesex (novel)|Middlesex}}|location=New York|publisher=Picador|section=Book 2, p. 99|url=https://archive.org/details/middlesex00euge_1\n|passage=My grandfather, accustomed to the multifarious conjugations of ancient Greek verbs, had found English, for all its incoherence, a relatively simple '''tongue''' to master.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete|synecdochically}} The [[speaker]]s of a [[language]], [[collectively]].\n#* {{RQ:KJV|Isaiah|66|18|text=I will gather all nations and '''tongues'''; and they shall come, and see my glory.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[voice]], {{gloss|the distinctive sound of a person's speech}}; [[accent]] {{gloss|distinctive manner of pronouncing a language}}.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Merchant of Venice|II|6|text=Who are you? Tell me, for more certainty,<br>Albeit I’ll swear that I do know your '''tongue'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Smollett Roderick Random|volume=1|chapter=21|page=173|text=[...] one of [the prisoners], whom by his '''tongue''' I knew to be a Scotchman, lamented most piteously [...]}}\n# A [[manner]] of [[speaking]], often [[habitually]].\n#: {{syn|en|mouth}}\n#: {{ux|en|She can have a [[sharp tongue|sharp '''tongue''']] when she's annoyed.}}\n#* {{c.|1515–1516}}, published 1568, {{w|John Skelton}}, ''Againſt venemous tongues enpoyſoned with ſclaunder and falſe detractions &c.'':\n#*: Al maters wel pondred and wel to be regarded,<br>How ſhuld a fals lying '''tung''' then be rewarded?\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1715|author=w:Daniel Defoe|title=The Family Instructor|location=London|publisher=Eman. Matthews|section=Volume 1, Part 2, Dialogue 2, p. 211|url=http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004844748.0001.001\n|passage=[...] his wicked way of Living, his prophane '''Tongue''', and his Contempt of Religion, had made him not very well receiv’d [...]}}\n#* {{RQ:Stevenson Kidnapped|chapter=The Death of the Red Fox|page=162|passage=\"Well,\" said he, at last, \"your '''tongue''' is bold; but I am no unfriend to plainness [...]\"}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1935|author=w:Dorothy L. Sayers|title=w:Gaudy Night|location=London|publisher=New English Library|year_published=1970|chapter=8|page=205|url=https://www.fadedpage.com/books/20140201/html.php\n|passage=I’m afraid I’ve inherited my uncle’s '''tongue''' and my mother’s want of tact.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1952|author=w:John Steinbeck|title={{w|East of Eden (novel)|East of Eden}}|location=London|publisher=Heinemann|section=Part 1, Chapter 2, p. 8|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.458774\n|passage=Samuel had no equal for soothing hysteria and bringing quiet to a frightened child. It was the sweetness of his '''tongue''' and the tenderness of his soul.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1972|author=w:Hortense Calisher|title=Herself|location=New York|publisher=Arbor House|section=Part 4, p. 369|url=https://archive.org/details/herself00hort\n|passage=[...] {{w|Frank Marcus}}’ ''{{w|The Killing of Sister George|Sister George}},'' technically a quite ordinary comedy in the old style [...] was remarkable [...] for the frank '''tongue''' of its Lesbians [...]}}\n# {{lb|en|synecdochically|usually|in the plural}} A person speaking in a specified manner.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1860|author=w:George Eliot|title=w:The Mill on the Floss|section=Book 7, Chapter 3|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/6688/6688-h/6688-h.htm\n|passage=I know that we must keep apart for a long while; cruel '''tongues''' would force us apart, if nothing else did.}}\n#* {{RQ:Mitchell Gone with the Wind|chapter=30|passage={{...}} it was obvious to his listeners that Pittypat, in his mind, was still a plump and charming miss of sixteen who must be sheltered against evil '''tongues'''.}}\n#* '''2007''', {{w|Ngũgĩ wa Thiong'o}}, ''{{w|Wizard of the Crow}},'' New York: Knopf Doubleday, Book 4, p.{{nbsp}}592,<sup>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=k5snFSTVhOsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false]</sup>\n#*: [...] the drunk, who had been a permanent fixture in that bar, changed location and thereafter moved from bar to bar, saying to inquisitive '''tongues''', Too long a stay in one seat tires the buttocks.\n# The power of articulate [[utterance]]; [[speech]] generally.\n#: {{ux|en|I was so overwhelmed my '''tongue''' deserted me.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1717|translator=w:John Dryden|title={{w|Ovid}}’s {{w|Metamorphoses}} in fifteen books|location=London|publisher=Jacob Tonson|chapter=The Story of Pygmalion and the Statue|page=344|url=http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004871123.0001.000\n|passage=Parrots imitating Human '''Tongue'''}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[discourse|Discourse]]; the [[fluency]] of [[speech]] or [[expression]].\n# {{lb|en|obsolete|uncountable}} [[discourse|Discourse]]; [[fluency]] of speech or expression.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 4-1|V|2|text=[...] fellows, soldiers, friends,<br>Better consider what you have to do<br>Than I, that have not well the gift of '''tongue''',<br>Can lift your blood up with persuasion.}}\n#* {{RQ:L'Estrange Fables of Aesop|text=Much '''Tongue''', and much Judgment seldom go together, for Talking and Thinking are Two Quite Differing Faculties,}}\n#* {{RQ:Eliot Daniel Deronda|II|XXXI|275|text=“[...] this Mr. Grandcourt has wonderful little '''tongue'''. Everything must be done dummy-like without his ordering.”<br>“Then he’s the more whip, I doubt,” said Mrs. Girdle. “''She’s'' got '''tongue''' enough, I warrant her [...]”}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[honorable|Honorable]] [[discourse]]; [[eulogy]].\n#* {{RQ:Beaumont Fletcher Comedies and Tragedies|Thierry and Theodoret|V|text=She was born noble; let that title find her<br>A private grave, but neither '''tongue''' nor honour!}}\n# {{lb|en|religion|often in the plural}} [[glossolalia|Glossolalia]].\n#: {{syn|en|speaking in tongues}}\n#* {{RQ:KJV|1 Corinthians|13|8|url=https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1%20Corinthians+13&version=KJV|text=Charity never faileth: but whether there be prophecies, they shall fail; whether there be '''tongues''', they shall cease; whether there be knowledge, it shall vanish away.}}\n# In a [[shoe]], the [[flap]] of [[material]] that goes between the [[laces]] and the [[foot]] (''so called because it resembles a tongue in the [[mouth]]'').\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1990|author=w:J. M. Coetzee|title=w:Age of Iron|url=https://archive.org/details/ageofiron00coet|chapter=3|page=96|publisher=Random House|location=New York\n|passage=I caught a glimpse of a brown boot, the '''tongue''' flapping, the sole tied on with string.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=w:Sarah Waters|title={{w|The Night Watch (Waters novel)|The Night Watch}}|location=London|publisher=Virago|chapter=2|page=53|url=https://archive.org/details/nightwatch00wate_0\n|passage=[...] her low-heeled shoes had flat fringed '''tongues''' to them—the kind of shoes you expected to see on a golf-course, or a Scottish highland, somewhere expensively hearty like that.}}\n# {{senseid|en|protrusion}} [[any|Any]] [[large]] or long physical [[protrusion]] on an automotive or machine part or any other part that fits into a long [[groove]] on another part.\n# A [[projection]], or slender [[appendage]] or [[fixture]].\n#: {{ux|en|the '''tongue''' of a [[buckle]], or of a [[balance]]}}\n# A [[long]], narrow [[strip]] of [[land]], projecting from the mainland into a sea or lake.\n#* {{quote-book\n|en\n|year=1851\n|author=w:Herman Melville\n|title=w:Moby-Dick\n|section=Chapter 12\n|passage=On one side was a coral reef; on the other a low '''tongue''' of land, covered with mangrove thickets that grew out into the water.}}\n# {{senseid|en|pole for towing or drawing}} The pole of a [[towed]] or drawn vehicle or farm implement (e.g., [[trailer]], [[cart]], [[plow]], [[harrow]]), by which it is pulled; for example, the [[pole]] of an [[ox]] [[cart]], to the end of which the oxen are yoked.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1986|author=w:Hortense Calisher|title=The Bobby-Soxer|url=https://archive.org/details/bobbysoxer00cali|page=91|publisher=Doubleday|location=Garden City, NY\n|passage=Far to the right, where the main pile sloped out, his cart reared '''tongue''' upward, like a plow.}}\n# The [[clapper]] of a [[bell]].\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Midsummer|V|1|text=The iron '''tongue''' of midnight hath told twelve:}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1940|author={{w|Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright}}|title=w:Native Son|location=London|publisher=Jonathan Cape|section=Book 2, p. 156|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.499539\n|passage=[...] the bell clanged so loud that he could hear the iron '''tongue''' clapping against the metal sides each time it swung to and fro [...]}}\n# {{lb|en|figuratively}} An individual [[point]] of [[flame]] from a [[fire]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1818|author=w:Percy Bysshe Shelley|title=w:The Revolt of Islam|location=London|publisher=C. and J. Ollier|section=Canto 3, stanza 13, p. 63|url=https://archive.org/details/revoltofislam00shel\n|passage=Then up a steep and dark and narrow stair<br>We wound, until the torches’ fiery '''tongue'''<br>Amid the gushing day beamless and pallid hung.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1895|author=H. G. Wells|title=The Time Machine|chapter=XI|passage=Now, in this decadent age the art of fire-making had been altogether forgotten on the earth. The red '''tongues''' that went licking up my heap of wood were an altogether new and strange thing to Weena.}}\n# A small [[sole]] (type of [[fish]]).\n# {{lb|en|nautical}} A short [[piece]] of [[rope]] [[splice]]d into the upper part of standing [[backstays]], etc.; also, the upper main piece of a [[mast]] composed of several pieces.\n# {{lb|en|music}} A [[reed]].\n# {{lb|en|geology}} A division of formation; A layer or member of a formation that pinches out in one direction.\n# {{lb|en|flags}} The middle [[protrusion]] of a triple-tailed [[flag]].\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|rop|tang}}\n* {{desc|bi|tang}}\n* {{desc|srn|tongo}}\n* {{desc|tpi|tang}}\n* {{desc|tcs|tang}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|organ}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Abkhaz: {{tt|ab|абз}}\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+|af|tong}}\n* Ahom: {{tt|aho|𑜎𑜢𑜃𑜫}}\n* Ainu: {{tt|ain|チャルンペ|tr=carunpe}}, {{tt|ain|パルンペ|tr=parunpe}}\n* Akan: {{t|ak|tɛkrɛma}}\n* Aklanon: {{tt|akl|dila'}}\n* Alawa: {{tt|alh|djeːjälŋ}}\n* Albanian: {{tt+|sq|gjuhë|f}}, {{t|sq|gu}}\n* Alviri-Vidari: {{tt|avd|زووان|tr=zuvān}} {{qualifier|Vidari}}\n* Ama: {{tt|amm|isauno}}\n* Amami Ōshima:\n*: Northern Amami Ōshima: {{tt|ryn|唇|tr=すぃば, sïba}}\n*: Southern Amami Ōshima: {{tt|ams|唇|tr=すぃび, sïba}}\n* Amharic: {{tt|am|ልሳን}}\n* Andi: {{tt|ani|мицӏцӏи}}\n* Ao: {{t|njo|temeli}}\n* Arabic: {{tt|ar|لِسَان|m|f}}\n*: Chadian Arabic: {{t|shu|لسان|m|tr=lisān}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|لسان|m|tr=lesān}}\n*: Gulf Arabic: {{t|afb|لسان|f|tr=lsān}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{tt|acw|لسان|m|tr=lisān}}\n*: 