rans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|food}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kieli}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|any similar organ}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kieli}}; {{tt+|fi|kärsä}} {{q|proboscis}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|language}}\n\n{{trans-top|obsolete: speakers of a language collectively}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kieli}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top-also|obsolete: voice|voice}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|puhe}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|manner of speaking}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kieli}}, {{tt+|fi|puhe}}, {{tt+|fi|puhetapa}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|person speaking in a specified manner}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kielet|p}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|power of utterance}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|puhe}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|obsolete: discourse, fluency of speech}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|uncountable: discourse, fluency of speech}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|puhe}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top-also|obsolete: honourable discourse|eulogy}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|religion: glossolalia|speaking in tongues}}\n\n{{trans-top|flap in a shoe}}\n* Ahtna: {{t|aht|ketsulaʼ}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|լեզվակ}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|ези́к|m}}\n* Cebuano: {{tt|ceb|dila}}, {{tt|ceb|diladila}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|鞋拔}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|jazyk|m}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|tong|c}}\n* Faroese: {{tt+|fo|tunga|f}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kieli}}, {{tt+|fi|iltti}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|languette|f}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Zunge|f}}, {{tt+|de|Lasche|f}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|γλώσσα|f}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|tunga|f}}, {{tt|is|tunga á skó|f}}, {{tt|is|skótunga|f}}\n* Ido: {{tt+|io|langeto}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|linguetta|f}}\n* Japanese: {{tt|ja|舌革|tr=したがわ, shitagawa}}, {{tt+|ja|タン|tr=tan}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{tt+|ckb|زمان}}\n* Malay: {{tt|ms|lidah kasut}}\n* Norwegian: {{tt+|no|tunge|c}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|język|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|língua|f}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|limbă|f}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|язычо́к|m}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|teanga|f}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|jazyk|m}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|lengüeta|f}}\n* Swahili: {{tt+|sw|ulimi}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|plös|c}}, {{tt+|sv|tunga|c}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|dil}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|clust|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|large or long physical protrusion}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kieli}}; {{t|fi|urospontti}} {{q|woodworking}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|a projection that fits into a slot}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kieli}}\n* Māori: {{tt|mi|teremū}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|projecting strip of land}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kieleke}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|pole of a vehicle}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|aisa}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|timon}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|timone}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|timón}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|clapper of a bell}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kieli}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|point of flame}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|lieska}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|type of fish}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kampela}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|nautical: piece of rope spliced into backstays; upper main piece of a mast}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|music: reed|reed}}\n\n{{trans-top|geology: division of formation}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Woiwurrung: {{t-check|wyi|jâllin}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====See also====\n* [[👅]]\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|music|ambitransitive}} On a [[wind]] instrument, to [[articulate]] a [[note]] by starting the air with a tap of the tongue, as though by speaking a 'd' or 't' sound ([[alveolar]] [[plosive]]).\n#: {{ux|en|Playing wind instruments involves '''tonguing''' on the reed or mouthpiece.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To manipulate with the tongue.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1985|author=Benjamin Capps|title=The Trail to Ogallala|publisher=TCU Press|isbn=9780875650135|page=88\n|text=[T]he cattle '''tongued''' at the damp grass, licking rather than grazing. {{...|They slobbered, leaving white bubbles along the ground, and seemed to lose more moisture than they gained from the dew.}}}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|slang|sometimes|vulgar}}<!--TBD: is this actually vulgar?--> To [[lick]], [[penetrate]] or [[manipulate]] with the tongue during [[flirt]]ing or [[oral sex]].\n#* {{RQ:Joyce Ulysses|chapter=8|passage=Hot I '''tongued''' her. She kissed me. I was kissed. All yielding she tossed my hair. Kissed, she kissed me. }}\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=1986-05-06|author=T.C. Boyle|title=Greasy Lake and Other Stories|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9781101462188\n|text=I was '''tonguing''' her ear and serenading her in a passionate whisper, mimicking Elvis, mimicking Joey.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=2024-10-29|author=Adriana Herrera|title=Heat and Run: A Steamy F/F/F Omegaverse Novella|publisher=Adriana Herrera\n|text=I was '''tonguing''' her sweet spot. \"Shit, that's nice.\" Her breaths got faster as we locked into a delicious rhythm that was hitting my clit just right. }}\n# To [[protrude]] in relatively long, narrow sections.\n#: {{ux|en|a soil horizon that '''tongues''' into clay}}\n# To join by means of a [[tongue and groove]].\n#: {{ux|en|to '''tongue''' boards together}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|obsolete}} To [[talk]]; to [[prate]].\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To speak; to utter.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Cymbeline|V|4|text=’Tis still a dream, or else such stuff as madmen<br>'''Tongue''' and brain not;}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To chide; to scold.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Measure|IV|4|text=How might she '''tongue''' me!}}\n\n===Derived terms===\n{{col4|en|title=Terms derived from the noun or verb ''tongue''|acid-tongued|birthtongue|hartstongue|houndstongue|loose-tongued|smoothtongue|subtongue|tonguectomy|tonguefucker|tongueful|tonguer|tonguetip|tonguy\n|adder's tongue\n|adder's-tongue\n|advanced tongue root|anti-tongues\n|beardtongue\n|beef tongue\n|betongue\n|bird's-tongue\n|birth tongue\n|birth-tongue\n|bite one's tongue\n|blab-tongue\n|blabtongue\n|black hairy tongue syndrome\n|bluetongue\n|blue-tongue\n|blue-to